    <p><strong><em>What Can You Do?</em></strong></p>
    <h3>Morning Announcement</h3>
    <p>Today&rsquo;s bullying prevention topic is &quot;What Can You Do?&quot; Everyone knows that bullying situations involve the student who's targeted and the student doing the bullying. Did you also know that many situations involve bystanders&mdash;students who aren't involved directly but see what's happening?</p>
    <p>Bystanders are powerful. In fact, more than half of bullying situations will end if bystanders step in. Direct confrontation is one way to intervene. Indirect help&mdash;such as not encouraging the situation or offering support to the person being bullied&mdash;is also effective. Bystanders can also let other students know that bullying is not okay. In your classroom today, you will be learning about different ways to respond to bullying situations. </p>
<h3> <strong>Classroom Education and Activities</strong></h3>
    <p>Active Learning and Discussion</p>
      <p><strong>Are you being bullied?</strong> Bullying can happen to anyone &ndash; and it&rsquo;s not so simple to recognize. Review these questions and learn more.</p>
      <ul>
      <li>Visit <a href="http://www.pacerteensagainstbullying.org/tab/bullying-defined/are-you-being-bullied/"><strong>PACERTeensAgainstBullying&gt;Bullying Defined</strong></a></li>
      </ul>
<p><strong>Could You Be the Bully?</strong> There is no typical student who bullies. Review these questions and learn more.</p>
<ul>
<li>Visit <a href="http://www.pacerteensagainstbullying.org/tab/bullying-defined/could-you-be-a-bully/"><strong>PACERTeensAgainstBullying&gt;Bullying Defined</strong></a></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Person First</strong> &ndash; Explain the importance of recognizing the person first, then his or her differences.</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Visit <a href="http://www.pacerteensagainstbullying.org/tab/experiencing-bullying/language-is-important/"><strong>PACERTeensAgainstBullying.org&gt;Language is Important</strong></a>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Educator Notes</strong> - <a href="/bullying/pdf/mh-starting-the-discussion-files/LanguageIsImportant.pdf" target="_blank"><strong>Language is Important</strong></a></li>
      </ul></li>
    </ul>
    <h3>Discussion Questions:</h3>
    <p><em>(To make sure all students participate, you may want to break the class into groups of 5 to 8 students. Appoint one student in each group to take notes and report results to the class. Consider using that feedback for future bullying prevention projects.)</em></p>
    <ul>
      <li>What are other ways that students can address bullying?</li>
      <li>What can you do in a cyberbullying situation?</li>
      <li>How does language affect how differences are perceived?</li>
      <li>What can someone who sees bullying do?</li>
      <li>What can teens do within their school to help prevent bullying?</li>
      <li>What options does someone who is being bullied have?</li>
    </ul>
    <h3>Video and Discussion</h3>
    <p>Watch &quot;Out of Bounds&quot; Video. Visit <a href="http://www.pacerteensagainstbullying.org/tab/experiencing-bullying/videos/"><strong>PACERTeensAgainstBullying.org&gt;ExperiencingBullying</strong></a><br />
Discussion Questions: </p>
    <ul>
      <li>What is the bullying situation?</li>
      <li>Who was involved in the bullying?</li>
      <li>How could this situation have been resolved more positively?</li>
    </ul>
